{{No footnotes|date=June 2014}}
'''Cain bairns''' or '''kain bairns''' were infants who, according to [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[superstition]], were seized by [[warlock]]s and [[witch]]es, and paid as a [[tax]] or [[tithe]] to the [[Devil]]. ''Càin'' is a Gaelic word for a [[tribute]], tax or tithe, and is the origin of the [[Scots language|Lowland Scots]] term. "[[Bairn]]", meaning child. The word was in use along the [[Scottish Borders]], according to [[Walter Scott]]'s ''Minstrelsy of the Scottish Border''.

It is unconnected with [[Cain]] in the [[Bible]].

